<br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><center>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Develop Your Idea First</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></center><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
Most people value their time. Posting a thread about this <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  great</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> idea you have for a comic and trying to sum it up in 3 sentences just isn't enough to convince the people you'd like to have onboard to join your group/circle whatever... unless of course they're really bored or have been impressed by your past work.<br>
<br>
Anyways, try to provide potential work-mates (and that's what it is kids, work) with enough information to let them decide if this is a project they'd really enjoy. Here are some suggestions:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Build a Site</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
You're going to need one anyway, right?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Develop Storylines</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
So what's the first issue about? How many pages does Issue #1 have? Does the series have an end point?...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Develop Characters</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
If you're an artistic type, draw profiles, design outfits, expressions etc. Writers should establish the motivations of the characters, create backgrounds for them, envision the world they live in.<br>
Research.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Determine Your Goals</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
So what will make this project successful? Is it a portfolio piece? Do you want to gather an online following? How many? Is this going to print?<br>
(And get ready for a whole new set of headaches if it is...)<br>
<br>
It's one thing to say, &quot;I've got this great idea...&quot;.<br>
It's another to say, &quot;Here, let me show you what I've got.&quot;<br>
